        "description": "All significant modelling assumptions (contact formulation, material constitutive model, geometric nonlinearity treatment, boundary condition idealisation) must be documented with physics-based justification. Sensitivity of QoIs to model form choices (e.g. bonded vs. frictional contact at screw–rod interface, linear vs. nonlinear material) must be quantified. The chosen model form must be shown to be the most physics-representative option within computational constraints."
      },
      "rationale": "Model form assumptions documented in MSP-FEA-F1717-NC-v3.2 Appendix B: (1) Frictional Coulomb contact (μ=0.2) at screw–rod interface — justified by tribological coupon tests; bonded contact alternative showed 12% stiffness over-prediction. (2) Bilinear isotropic hardening (BISO) for Ti-6Al-4V — justified by tensile coupon data; elastic-perfectly-plastic alternative showed 8% yield force under-prediction. (3) Large-deformation (NLGEOM ON) — required for >5% strain in screw shank at 40 mm displacement. (4) UHMWPE surrogate block modelled as linear elastic with E=1.0 GPa — validated against block compression tests (error <3%). Sensitivity study confirms QoI sensitivity to friction coefficient (±0.05 → ±4.1% stiffness) is the dominant model form uncertainty, captured in UQ. Gradation 5 achieved: full physics completeness assessment with quantified model form sensitivity."
