    "actor": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/actor/credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team — V&V 40 lead analyst and independent reviewer",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw FEA model under ASTM F1717 static compression-bending is ACCEPTED at Model Risk Level 5 under the Complete profile. All 13 ASME V&V 40 credibility factors have been assessed; 12 of 13 factors meet or exceed their required gradation level, and the 13th (Test conditions) achieves exactly the required Gradation 3 with no shortfall. Key evidence supporting acceptance: (1) Validation metric E/uval < 1.96 for all three primary QoIs across both laboratories and the pooled dataset, with the most demanding value being 1.44 for force-at-40mm — well within the pre-specified acceptance threshold. (2) All QoI differences < 5.7%, well within the pre-established 10% acceptance bound. (3) Mesh convergence GCI < 0.5% for all QoIs, confirming discretization error is negligible. (4) Ensemble consistency across three independent FEA solvers (maximum inter-solver spread 2.1%) provides strong evidence of model robustness. (5) Sobol' sensitivity analysis (n=8192 QMC samples, second-order indices) identifies cortical shell thickness and screw–rod interface friction as dominant variance contributors, with combined first-order Sobol' indices accounting for 78% of output variance — confirming the model is well-characterised and not dominated by unknown interactions. (6) Full provenance chain from raw experimental data through validation results to this decision record is documented and traceable. (7) The Complete-profile high-MRL pathway requirements are fully satisfied: inline sensitivity analysis documentation, concrete operating envelope bounds, and substantive applicability constraint are all present. No offset rationale is required as no factor has achievedLevel < requiredLevel.",
